<HEADLINE>
<P>
AMERICAN LEAGUE ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
YANKEES BEAT INDIANS IN OPENER, 6-4 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dave Winfield missed the 1989 season with back problems and went one for 29 in 
spring training, fueling speculation the 12-time All-Star outfielder might not 
be able to come back at age 38. 
</P>
<P>
But Thursday at New York, Winfield doubled and scored the New York Yankees' 
first run in a 6-4 victory over the Cleveland Indians in a much-delayed season 
opener. 
</P>
<P>
The teams were rained out Tuesday and snowed out Wednesday at Cleveland. They 
returned to Yankee Stadium for a game, rescheduled because of the lockout, and 
became the last two major league clubs to start the season. 
</P>
<P>
"Everything I do is kind of new," Winfield said. "It's like I'm a rookie." 
</P>
<P>
A crowd of 50,114 saw the Yankees win their fifth consecutive opener and John 
McNamara lose his first game as manager of the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
Pinch-hitter Luis Polonia, batting for rookie Mike Blowers, singled home the 
tiebreaking run off reliever Doug Jones in the eighth inning. 
</P>
<P>
Eric Plunk, the Yankees' fourth pitcher, went 1 1/3 innings for the victory. 
</P>
<P>
Cory Snyder, who had a home run wiped out by the snow on Wednesday, hit a 
two-run homer off Dave LaPoint in the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
Yankee first baseman Don Mattingly, a notorious slow starter, had two hits, 
including a run-scoring single. Mattingly is a .285 lifetime hitter in April, 
38 points below his career average. 
</P>
<P>
Detroit 11, Boston 7 -- Lou Whitaker hit the 150th home run of his career and 
Tony Phillips had four hits at Detroit to help the Tigers end an 11-game losing 
streak against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
Whitaker's two-run homer off rookie Mike Rochford in the first inning gave 
Detroit a 2-1 lead. 
</P>
<P>
Phillips singled in two more runs during a four-run second inning. 
</P>
<P>
Former Angel right-hander Urbano Lugo relieved Frank Tanana in the fifth and 
earned his first victory for Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
Tony Pena hit his first home run for the Red Sox in the fourth inning. 
</P>
<P>
Toronto 7, Texas 1 -- Fred McGriff, Pat Borders and Kelly Gruber hit home runs 
to lead the Blue Jays at Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
McGriff's second-inning homer off Jamie Moyer was his first in his past 108 
at-bats and tied the score, 1-1. McGriff led the American League with 36 home 
runs last season, but his last homer was on Sept. 4 against the Chicago White 
Sox at Comiskey Park. 
</P>
<P>
Borders hit a solo homer and Gruber had a three-run home run during a four-run 
seventh. 
</P>
<P>
Mike Flanagan (1-0) allowed five singles in five innings, struck out one and 
walked none. 
</P>
<P>
Moyer (0-1) allowed four runs and nine hits in six-plus innings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
