<TEXT>
<P>
They look like they should be hanging from the ceiling, but in reality, they 
are the newest accessory for ears. They're earrings shaped like chandeliers. 
</P>
<P>
Made of crystal, gold, silver, pearls and semi precious stones, most of them 
are long enough to brush the shoulders -- at least. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles jewelry designer Deanna Hamro was on top of the trend two years 
ago, but it was just recently that the demand caught up with her vision. 
</P>
<P>
Her 24-karat gold door-knockers with gold chains and lavender Austrian pave 
crystals for $405 (pictured here) are available at Buffalo in Tarzana. 
</P>
<P>
Pamela McGivern, a San Francisco jewelry designer, calls her line of 
Victorian-looking gold filigree and pearl earrings Chandel Ears. Priced from 
$185 to $265, they are available at Fred Hayman Beverly Hills. 
</P>
<P>
You can have your earrings as long as you please by ordering gold or silver 
pearls by the inch at Faux Body Ornaments. 
</P>
<P>
Designed by Hillary Ellison, a pair measuring up to seven inches run $98. 
</P>
<P>
At Madeleine Gallay, an incredibly long pair of earrings designed by Eric 
Beamon go for $210. They are made of Austrian crystals, pearls and beads. 
JOANNA DENDEL 
</P>
