</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hardest Working Man?: Imprisoned soul singer James Brown was freed from prison 
Thursday after 16 months to begin a work-release program. Brown will act as a 
counselor with the Aiken and Barnwell Counties Community Action Commission in 
Aiken, S.C. Brown, often billed as the "hardest-working man in show business," 
likely would be required to talk with children and adults in the largely rural 
area and work to increase public awareness of the poor. He will spend nights 
and weekends at a minimum security prison in Aiken County. GREG BRAXTON 
