<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: BUENA PARK; 
</P>
<P>
VFW POST IS GIVEN ULTIMATUM BY CITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNDA NATALI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After emotional testimony from members of the Veterans of Foreign Wars post 
here, the Planning Commission agreed unanimously this week to give the veterans 
six months to either vacate their hall or comply with their use permit and 
install a new parking area. 
</P>
<P>
The post has been looking for a place to relocate since the City Council barred 
it last September from renting its facility to outside groups because of gripes 
from neighbors around the hall. 
</P>
<P>
VFW leaders say that renting out the hall was their main source of income. 
</P>
<P>
Neighbors had complained of noise and litter caused by weddings and other large 
gatherings held in the hall. The problems came to a head last March when 
gunshots were fired in front of the lodge during a party. No one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
Angry veterans lashed out at the commission Wednesday night, saying that they 
being victimized. 
</P>
<P>
"A lot of these people bought their homes after the VFW was there," said John 
Curry, a member of the post. 
</P>
<P>
The veterans told the commission that they are having trouble selling the hall 
and finding a suitable place to relocate. 
</P>
<P>
"We can't afford to go anywhere else unless we can sell it," Curry told the 
commission. 
</P>
<P>
Since the rental restrictions have gone into place, the VFW post has had to cut 
down on many of its charitable efforts, including visiting hospital-bound 
veterans during the holidays, members say. LYNDA NATALI 
</P>
</TEXT>
